For matrix multiplication, (AB)^T = B^T A^T.

This can be shown as follows:
Let A be a m x n matrix and B be a n x p matrix. 
Then, 
A = [a_{ij}]  (m x n)
B = [b_{ij}]  (n x p)

AB = [c_{ij}]  (m x p)  where c_{ij} = \sum_{k=1}^{n} a_{ik} b_{kj}

(AB)^T = [d_{ij}]  (p x m)  where d_{ij} = c_{ji} 
B^T = [e_{ij}]  (p x n) where e_{ij} = b_{ji}
A^T = [f_{ij}]  (n x m) where f_{ij} = a_{ji}

Then, 
d_{ij} = \sum_{k=1}^{n} e_{ik} f_{kj} = \sum_{k=1}^{n} b_{ki} a_{jk}

Which shows (AB)^T = B^T A^T.

So in short, for matrix multiplication, the transpose of the product of two matrices is equal to the product of their transposes in reverse order.

Here is a JavaScript function that will check if any of the numbers in an array of 5 numbers is a prime number:

```js
function checkForPrime(nums) {
  for (let i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
    let isPrime = true;
    for (let j = 2; j < nums[i]; j++) {
      if (nums[i] % j === 0) {
        isPrime = false;
        break;
      }
    }
    if (isPrime) {
      console.log(nums[i] + ' is a prime number!');
    }
  }
}
```

This function loops through each number in the array. For each number, it checks if it is divisible by any number between 2 and the number itself. If not, then the number is prime and it prints it to the console.

